04610nam a22006975i 9781503603776DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017028678  a97815036037767 a10.1515/97815036037762doi  a(DE-B1597)564591  a(OCoLC)1198929730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aD638.L43bT36 2018 4aD638.L43 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a940.3/5692223  aNP 64502rvk1 aTanielian, Melanie S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Charity of War :bFamine, Humanitarian Aid, and World War I in the Middle East /cMelanie S. Tanielian. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTE ON TRANSLITERATION -- tIntroduction Total War: Politics, Power, and Benevolence -- t1. A City and Its Mountain, a Mountain and Its City -- t2. Wartime Famine: Strategies, Logistics, and Catastrophe -- t3. The Politics of Food: Wartime Provisioning for Civilians -- t4. Prayers and Patrons: The Politics of Neutrality -- t5. Rats, Lice, and Microbes: The Struggle against Infectious Diseases -- t6. Local Relief Initiatives: Civil Society, Women, and the State -- t7. Beneficial Benevolence: International Wartime Relief Efforts -- tConclusion: Beirut 1919: The Chaos of Memory and Politics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the exception of a few targeted aerial bombardments of the city's port, Beirut and Mount Lebanon did not see direct combat in World War I. Yet civilian casualties in this part of the Ottoman Empire reached shocking heights, possibly numbering half a million people. No war, in its usual understanding, took place there, but Lebanon was incontestably war-stricken. As a food crisis escalated into famine, it was the bloodless incursion of starvation and the silent assault of fatal disease that defined everyday life. The Charity of War tells how the Ottoman home front grappled with total war and how it sought to mitigate starvation and sickness through relief activities. Melanie S. Tanielian examines the wartime famine's reverberations throughout the community: in Beirut's municipal institutions, in its philanthropic and religious organizations, in international agencies, and in the homes of the city's residents. Her local history reveals a dynamic politics of provisioning that was central to civilian experiences in the war, as well as to the Middle Eastern political landscape that emerged post-war. By tracing these responses to the conflict, she demonstrates World War I's immediacy far from the European trenches, in a place where war was a socio-economic and political process rather than a military event.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFamineszLebanonxHistoryy20th century. 0aHumanitarian assistancezLebanonxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xCivilian reliefzLebanon. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xFood supplyzLebanon. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xHealth aspectszLebanon. 4aBeirut. 4aLebanon. 4aMiddle East. 4aOttoman Empire. 4aWorld War I. 4acivilians. 4afamine. 4ahome front. 4ahumanitarianism. 4awar relief. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360377640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603776.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles